awd_titl_txt: New Modes of Metallacycle and Carbene Reactivity
awd_abstract_narration: In this project supported by the Inorganic, Bioinorganic, and                   Organometallic Chemistry Program, Joseph M. O'Connor of the                     University of Nevada at Reno will continue studies in the area                  of organometallic research at the interface of metallacycle and                 carbene chemistry.  The goal of the research is development of                  new carbene coupling reactions which produce ring-expanded                      metallacycles of iridum, rhodium, or cobalt and ultimately                      four- and five-membered carbocycles.  Free carbene-carbene                      products may also be generated.  In addition to the synthetic                   work, structural and mechanistic studies will be carried out in                 order to clarify the effect of coordination geometry, ancillary                 ligands, and ring substituents on the insertion process.                        %%%                                                                             This research directly impinges on the role of metal carbenes                   in alkene metathesis, alkene and alkyne polymerization,                         cyclopropanation chemistry and an impressive array of synthetic                 organic methodology.
